    Introduction

    In this Lab Step, you'll learn about the basics of Helm. You'll learn how to use the helm create command to scaffold or generate an empty Helm Chart test-app project. You'll then learn to use the helm template command to generate an actual manifest file which can then be deployed into a Kubernetes cluster.

    Notes:

    • Helm 2.0 is used
    • The empty Helm Chart test-app project that you create in this Lab Step will NOT be deployed into the Kubernetes cluster, it is only being used to demonstrate how to create and scaffold new Helm based projects. In the next Lab Step you'll get to deploy an existing Helm templated project into the cluster.

    Instructions  

    1. For starters navigate up one directory into the lab/code/App/lab-code/ directory. In the terminal execute the following command:

    cd ..

    2. Use the helm create command to generate a new Helm Chart project named test-app. In the terminal execute the following command:

    helm create test-app

     

    3. To examine the structure of the new Helm test-app project, install the tree utility. In the terminal execute the following command:

    sudo yum install -y tree

    4. Use the tree command to render out the directory structure to the screen. In the terminal execute the following command:

    tree test-app/

     

    Take some time to examine the test-app directory and the newly generated defaul template files within the IDE editor view. By doing so you will become familiar with the structure, design and intent of these files.

    5. Use the helm template command to convert the Helm templates into a single deployable Kubernetes manifest file. In the terminal execute the following command:

    helm template test-app/

    Review the output of the previous helm template command. Take some time to understand how the default values contained within the test-app/values.yaml file have been injected into their respective placeholders within each of the test-app/templates/*.yaml files.

     

    Summary

    In this Lab Step, you learnt how to use the helm create command to scaffold an empty Helm Chart project. You then learnt how to use the helm template command to generate an actual deployable manifest file. In the next Lab Step you will use both the helm and kubectl commands together to perform an actual Kubernetes cluster deployment.
